issues in the US.

26
00:01:11,130 --> 00:01:13,480
And certainly if you want to
learn more about it, you can

27
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:15,650
learn more in 14.41.

28
00:01:15,650 --> 00:01:18,910
So I want to start by talking
about the first side of the

29
00:01:18,910 --> 00:01:21,540
transfer equation, putting
money in the bucket, and

30
00:01:21,540 --> 00:01:22,790
that's taxation.

31
00:01:22,790 --> 00:01:27,640

32
00:01:27,640 --> 00:01:33,020
Talk about taxation, putting
the money in the bucket.

33
00:01:33,020 --> 00:01:35,320
We have a number of sorts
of taxation in the US.

34
00:01:35,320 --> 00:01:37,300
I mean, look at the first
page of the handout.

35
00:01:37,300 --> 00:01:40,250
This pie chart gives a breakdown
of where we raise

36
00:01:40,250 --> 00:01:42,060
our money as a government
in the US.

37
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:43,420
So if you want to redistribute,
first you've got

38
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:43,920
to raise money.

39
00:01:43,920 --> 00:01:45,300
How do we raise it?

40
00:01:45,300 --> 00:01:48,480
Well basically, the majority
of the money we raise is

41
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:51,470
raised through the income tax.

42
00:01:51,470 --> 00:01:54,760
The income tax is a tax
on families' incomes.

43
00:01:54,760 --> 00:01:58,180
And importantly, it's what we
call a progressive, so the

44
00:01:58,180 --> 00:02:00,620
majority of money raised
from the income tax.

45
00:02:00,620 --> 00:02:04,560
The income tax is what we
call a progressive tax.

46
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:08,990
What that means is the richer
you are, the higher share of

47
00:02:08,990 --> 00:02:11,740
income you pay in taxation.

48
00:02:11,740 --> 00:02:12,300
Progressive.

49
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:15,380
As opposed to regressive tax,
is one where the richer you

50
00:02:15,380 --> 00:02:16,860
are, the lower the percentage
of your

51
00:02:16,860 --> 00:02:18,980
income you pay in taxation.

52
00:02:18,980 --> 00:02:21,480
And once again, obviously
progressive/regressive has

53
00:02:21,480 --> 00:02:23,150
some normative feel to it.

54
00:02:23,150 --> 00:02:25,600
And the notion is once again,
under most social welfare

55
00:02:25,600 --> 00:02:29,360
functions, we're going to want a
function which redistributes

56
00:02:29,360 --> 00:02:30,680
from rich to poor.

57
00:02:30,680 --> 00:02:33,600
And that's a progressive
income tax system does.

58
00:02:33,600 --> 00:02:36,330
So if you look at the next
page of the handout, this

59
00:02:36,330 --> 00:02:41,920
shows for current year, I think
it's for 2010, maybe

60
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:46,180
2009, what tax rates look
like in the US.

61
00:02:46,180 --> 00:02:50,330
Now it's important to remember a
distinction between marginal

62
00:02:50,330 --> 00:02:53,420
tax rates and the taxes
you actually pay.

63
00:02:53,420 --> 00:02:56,130
What this graph shows is
your marginal tax rate.

64
00:02:56,130 --> 00:02:59,970
What that means is for the next
dollar that you earn,

65
00:02:59,970 --> 00:03:01,990
what percent do you
pay in taxes?

66
00:03:01,990 --> 00:03:08,440
So for example, for someone who
earns less than $16,700,

67
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:13,210
for every dollar they earn,
they pay $0.10 in taxes.

68
00:03:13,210 --> 00:03:16,300
In fact, everybody pays that on
the first $16,700 they pay.

69
00:03:16,300 --> 00:03:21,590
So Bill Gates, on the first
$16,700 he earns pays $0.10.

70
00:03:21,590 --> 00:03:26,370
Then on every dollar beyond
that, you pay $0.15 till

71
00:03:26,370 --> 00:03:28,600
you've earned $67,900.

72
00:03:28,600 --> 00:03:32,950
Then you pay $0.25 and so on
until on every dollar above

73
00:03:32,950 --> 00:03:38,700
$373,000, you're paying $0.35.

74
00:03:38,700 --> 00:03:40,290
And the key point is these
are the marginal rates.

75
00:03:40,290 --> 00:03:46,990
So if your income is
$350,000, then your

76
00:03:46,990 --> 00:03:49,070
marginal rate is 33%.

77
00:03:49,070 --> 00:03:51,210
You're on the next to
the last bracket.

78
00:03:51,210 --> 00:03:53,330
But along the way, you've
paid lower rates.

79
00:03:53,330 --> 00:03:59,000
You pay the 10% on your first
$16,700 and so on.

80
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,790
But the bottom line, this is a
progressive system where the

81
00:04:01,790 --> 00:04:04,560
higher your income, the more
you pay in tax on the next

82
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:06,170
dollar earned.

83
00:04:06,170 --> 00:04:07,660
OK, and that's the way
the income tax works.

84
00:04:07,660 --> 00:04:09,330
And there's a lot of
other complicated

85
00:04:09,330 --> 00:04:10,610
features we can get into.

86
00:04:10,610 --> 00:04:14,070
But roughly speaking, you take
your income and you tax it

87
00:04:14,070 --> 00:04:14,920
progressively.

88
00:04:14,920 --> 00:04:18,730
And that determines what
you pay the government.

89
00:04:18,730 --> 00:04:23,910
Now if we flip back to the first
page, the second major

90
00:04:23,910 --> 00:04:25,680
source of revenues for the US

91
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:29,740
government is payroll taxation.

92
00:04:29,740 --> 00:04:36,470
This is different from income
taxation in that this is a

93
00:04:36,470 --> 00:04:39,440
flat percent tax.

94
00:04:39,440 --> 00:04:42,050
So this is not progressive or
regressive, it's neutral.

95
00:04:42,050 --> 00:04:43,760
It a flat percent of
your income you

96
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:46,700
pay in payroll taxation.

97
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:49,180
So unlike the income tax where
the richer you are,

98
00:04:49,180 --> 00:04:50,810
the more you pay.

99
00:04:50,810 --> 00:04:53,740
Here you pay a certain
flat percentage

100
00:04:53,740 --> 00:04:54,990
regardless of income.

101
00:04:54,990 --> 00:04:59,220
And this money goes to finance
the nation's--

102
00:04:59,220 --> 00:05:01,550
what's called the nation's
social insurance program.

103
00:05:01,550 --> 00:05:03,580
And we'll focus on
that on Monday.

104
00:05:03,580 --> 00:05:07,440
But basically goes to finance
programs that help people if

105
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:12,130
they suffer negative risks, like
get unemployed or need

106
00:05:12,130 --> 00:05:13,830
health care, et cetera.

107
00:05:13,830 --> 00:05:15,430
That's financed by
the payroll tax.

108
00:05:15,430 --> 00:05:18,790

109
00:05:18,790 --> 00:05:23,135
The third source of taxation
is consumption taxation.

110
00:05:23,135 --> 00:05:26,480

111
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:29,250
Consumption taxation.

112
00:05:29,250 --> 00:05:33,610
As we can see in the US, that is
the third largest source of

113
00:05:33,610 --> 00:05:37,040
revenues, about 15.7% of
government revenues come from

114
00:05:37,040 --> 00:05:38,920
consumption taxes.

115
00:05:38,920 --> 00:05:41,010
Now these are of two types.

116
00:05:41,010 --> 00:05:43,190
These are taxes on
consumption.

117
00:05:43,190 --> 00:05:44,110
There are two types.

118
00:05:44,110 --> 00:05:46,790
One type is the sales tax.

119
00:05:46,790 --> 00:05:49,550
So in Massachusetts this is the
6 and a quarter percent.

120
00:05:49,550 --> 00:05:51,870
Everything you buy in certain
categories, you pay 6 and a

121
00:05:51,870 --> 00:05:55,850
quarter percent extra that
goes to the state.

122
00:05:55,850 --> 00:06:01,740
The other is excise taxes, which
are specific taxes that

123
00:06:01,740 --> 00:06:03,500
are levied on specific goods.

124
00:06:03,500 --> 00:06:05,290
So there's an excise
tax on cigarettes.

125
00:06:05,290 --> 00:06:08,030

126
00:06:08,030 --> 00:06:11,270
You pay a certain dollar amount
per pack of cigarettes

127
00:06:11,270 --> 00:06:12,400
in excise tax.

128
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:14,010
Excise tax on alcohol.

129
00:06:14,010 --> 00:06:16,410
Excise tax on gasoline.

130
00:06:16,410 --> 00:06:21,180
So these are specific
taxes on goods.

131
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:25,610
And the important thing is these
consumption taxes are

132
00:06:25,610 --> 00:06:27,875
often called indirect taxes.

133
00:06:27,875 --> 00:06:30,460

134
00:06:30,460 --> 00:06:33,560
Because unlike income and
payroll taxes where you earn

135
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:35,190
$1, you pay tax on it.

136
00:06:35,190 --> 00:06:38,020
Here you don't pay the tax
till you spend the money.

137
00:06:38,020 --> 00:06:39,540
So the consumption tax
does not tax you

138
00:06:39,540 --> 00:06:41,090
directly on your income.

139
00:06:41,090 --> 00:06:44,200
It taxes you as you use your
income to buy things.

140
00:06:44,200 --> 00:06:45,550
So it's often called
the indirect tax.

141
00:06:45,550 --> 00:06:49,770

142
00:06:49,770 --> 00:06:53,845
The fourth major source of tax
revenues is the property tax.

143
00:06:53,845 --> 00:06:59,590

144
00:06:59,590 --> 00:07:02,820
This is a tax that you pay
on your actual wealth.

145
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:04,790
This is the third kind of tax.

146
00:07:04,790 --> 00:07:08,110
So the first kind of tax we
tax you on your earnings,

147
00:07:08,110 --> 00:07:09,990
either through income
or payroll taxes.

148
00:07:09,990 --> 00:07:13,120
A second kind of tax, they tax
you on your consumption.

149
00:07:13,120 --> 00:07:15,410
A third kind of tax, they
tax you on your wealth.

150
00:07:15,410 --> 00:07:21,060
So literally every year, you pay
a certain fraction of the

151
00:07:21,060 --> 00:07:24,530
value of your house, for
example, in a property tax to

152
00:07:24,530 --> 00:07:25,250
your local government.

153
00:07:25,250 --> 00:07:26,900
So it's another form
of taxation.

154
00:07:26,900 --> 00:07:30,300
That's where we get about
10% of our revenues.

155
00:07:30,300 --> 00:07:33,060
And then finally, there's
the corporate

156
00:07:33,060 --> 00:07:37,860
tax, which is a tax--

157
00:07:37,860 --> 00:07:41,130
this is sort of akin
to the income tax.

158
00:07:41,130 --> 00:07:43,030
But instead of levied on
individuals, it's levied on

159
00:07:43,030 --> 00:07:43,930
corporations.

160
00:07:43,930 --> 00:07:46,430
It's money that corporations
pay as they

161
00:07:46,430 --> 00:07:47,680
earn more in profits.

162
00:07:47,680 --> 00:07:50,060

163
00:07:50,060 --> 00:07:53,740
So we tax lots of different
sources of income.

164
00:07:53,740 --> 00:07:56,950
We tax you lots of different
ways in the US.

165
00:07:56,950 --> 00:08:01,800
If you add it up overall,
we pay about 20% of

166
00:08:01,800 --> 00:08:03,750
our income in taxation.

167
00:08:03,750 --> 00:08:07,150
That is every dollar that's
earned in the US, about $0.20

168
00:08:07,150 --> 00:08:09,540
goes to the government
on average.

169
00:08:09,540 --> 00:08:10,465
Now obviously it's different.

170
00:08:10,465 --> 00:08:11,440
If you're richer, it's higher.

171
00:08:11,440 --> 00:08:12,355
If you're poor, it's less.

172
00:08:12,355 --> 00:08:14,380
It depends on how much you
consume, et cetera.

173
00:08:14,380 --> 00:08:15,460
And your wealth, et cetera.

174
00:08:15,460 --> 00:08:20,610
But overall across everyone, on
average, about 20% of our

175
00:08:20,610 --> 00:08:23,030
income goes to taxation.

176
00:08:23,030 --> 00:08:25,850
About one fifth of our GDP.

177
00:08:25,850 --> 00:08:29,190
The problem we have right now
is if you look at government

178
00:08:29,190 --> 00:08:32,429
spending, that's more
like a quarter.

179
00:08:32,429 --> 00:08:35,150
It's 24% of GDP.

180
00:08:35,150 --> 00:08:38,500
So we collect about a fifth of
our national income in taxes,

181
00:08:38,500 --> 00:08:40,610
but we spend about a quarter.

182
00:08:40,610 --> 00:08:42,250
Thus we have a more
than trillion

183
00:08:42,250 --> 00:08:44,430
dollar national deficit.

184
00:08:44,430 --> 00:08:47,340
So the problem we have right now
is we're collecting a lot

185
00:08:47,340 --> 00:08:51,270
less in taxes than we're
spending as a government.

186
00:08:51,270 --> 00:08:54,170
Now, we're not going to get
into what's behind that.

187
00:08:54,170 --> 00:08:56,610
That has both some structural
sources,

188
00:08:56,610 --> 00:08:57,640
which we'll talk about.

189
00:08:57,640 --> 00:09:01,490
Most notably the incredible rise
in medical care spending.

190
00:09:01,490 --> 00:09:03,490
And it has some cyclical
sources, which is in a

191
00:09:03,490 --> 00:09:07,680
recession, naturally you spend
more because people need more

192
00:09:07,680 --> 00:09:10,320
help from the government and you
tax less because there's

193
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:12,180
less income to be taxed.

194
00:09:12,180 --> 00:09:14,300
So some of the reason we have
this huge deficit is that

195
00:09:14,300 --> 00:09:15,640
we're in a recession still.

196
00:09:15,640 --> 00:09:17,810
We haven't come out of it yet.

197
00:09:17,810 --> 00:09:20,345
Some of it is more structural in
that we have fundamentally

198
00:09:20,345 --> 00:09:23,610
a system which is spending
beyond our means.

199
00:09:23,610 --> 00:09:25,000
And we'll talk a bit
more about that.

200
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:28,180

201
00:09:28,180 --> 00:09:33,930
What I want to focus on now
is given this large set of

202
00:09:33,930 --> 00:09:36,760
different things we should tax,
I want to focus on one

203
00:09:36,760 --> 00:09:37,545
specific question.

204
00:09:37,545 --> 00:09:39,240
There's lots questions
we could focus on.

205
00:09:39,240 --> 00:09:41,770
And once again, in 14.41, we
talk about a lot of them.

206
00:09:41,770 --> 00:09:43,800
But I want to focus today on
one question of particular

207
00:09:43,800 --> 00:09:46,840
interest. Which is, what
should we tax?

208
00:09:46,840 --> 00:09:50,780
I've just laid out here five
different things we can tax.

209
00:09:50,780 --> 00:09:53,075
We can tax your income,
either progressively

210
00:09:53,075 --> 00:09:54,810
or in a flat tax.

211
00:09:54,810 --> 00:09:55,930
We can tax your consumption.

212
00:09:55,930 --> 00:09:57,280
We can tax your property.

213
00:09:57,280 --> 00:09:59,080
We can tax corporations.

214
00:09:59,080 --> 00:10:01,000
What should we tax?

215
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,930
If we're going to raise this
20%, why do we do it in all

216
00:10:02,930 --> 00:10:05,460
these different ways?

217
00:10:05,460 --> 00:10:09,230
For example, in Europe, taxation
is very different.

218
00:10:09,230 --> 00:10:13,170
In Europe, they raise much less
through income taxation

219
00:10:13,170 --> 00:10:16,280
and much more through
consumption taxation.

220
00:10:16,280 --> 00:10:18,990
They have something in Europe
called the value-added tax.

221
00:10:18,990 --> 00:10:20,910
You guys may have dealt with it
if you've traveled there,

222
00:10:20,910 --> 00:10:22,790
traveled abroad-- the VAT.

223
00:10:22,790 --> 00:10:24,500
The value-added tax is basically
their version

224
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:26,530
of the sales tax.

225
00:10:26,530 --> 00:10:29,610
It's basically a sales tax, but
each level of producer is

226
00:10:29,610 --> 00:10:33,660
tax on the value they
add to production.

227
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:36,140
And so in Europe, they tax
consumption a lot more and

228
00:10:36,140 --> 00:10:37,390
income a lot less.

229
00:10:37,390 --> 00:10:39,630

230
00:10:39,630 --> 00:10:40,680
Is that a good idea or not?

231
00:10:40,680 --> 00:10:44,080
For example, one of the two
major deficit commissions

232
00:10:44,080 --> 00:10:46,620
that's just reporting these last
couple weeks on ways to

233
00:10:46,620 --> 00:10:48,810
get down the deficit, has
suggested we actually

234
00:10:48,810 --> 00:10:52,620
introduce a national sales tax
to move towards more like

235
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:55,160
Europe and have more of our
taxation based on consumption

236
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:57,570
and less based on income.

237
00:10:57,570 --> 00:11:00,250
What's the major argument
for this?

238
00:11:00,250 --> 00:11:04,260
Well, the major argument for
taxing consumption instead of

239
00:11:04,260 --> 00:11:06,880
taxing income comes back to what
we talked about a couple

240
00:11:06,880 --> 00:11:07,950
lectures ago.

241
00:11:07,950 --> 00:11:11,540
Which is that it promotes
savings.

242
00:11:11,540 --> 00:11:13,990
Remember, income can
be defined as

243
00:11:13,990 --> 00:11:15,270
consumption plus savings.

244
00:11:15,270 --> 00:11:18,090
You take your income and you
either consume it or save it.

245
00:11:18,090 --> 00:11:19,290
OK

246
00:11:19,290 --> 00:11:24,670
When we tax income, then we tax
both your consumption and

247
00:11:24,670 --> 00:11:25,920
your savings.

248
00:11:25,920 --> 00:11:28,000

249
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:33,730
When we tax consumption only,
we don't tax your savings.

250
00:11:33,730 --> 00:11:37,870
Assuming substitution effects
dominate, that will therefore

251
00:11:37,870 --> 00:11:39,540
promote savings.

252
00:11:39,540 --> 00:11:42,620
Taxing consumption rather
than taxing income

253
00:11:42,620 --> 00:11:44,770
will promote savings.

254
00:11:44,770 --> 00:11:48,690
Once again, assuming
substitution effects dominate.

255
00:11:48,690 --> 00:11:51,410
