00:45:30,340 --> 00:45:33,890
So while the EITC incentivizes
you to work when you're low

998
00:45:33,890 --> 00:45:40,410
income, it disincentivizes work
when your income goes up.

999
00:45:40,410 --> 00:45:44,760
So this is once again why public
policy is fun and hard,

1000
00:45:44,760 --> 00:45:45,970
which is there's a trade-off.

1001
00:45:45,970 --> 00:45:47,350
There's always a trade-off
in this course.

1002
00:45:47,350 --> 00:45:49,250
It's really annoying.

1003
00:45:49,250 --> 00:45:52,110
There's a trade-off, which is
on the one hand, we want to

1004
00:45:52,110 --> 00:45:54,580
target our program to give
the money to the

1005
00:45:54,580 --> 00:45:57,570
lowest income groups.

1006
00:45:57,570 --> 00:45:59,360
On the other hand, if you target
something, that means

1007
00:45:59,360 --> 00:46:02,170
you have to take it away.

1008
00:46:02,170 --> 00:46:05,370
Targeting equals taking away.

1009
00:46:05,370 --> 00:46:07,490
What that means is by targeting
to the lowest income

1010
00:46:07,490 --> 00:46:10,150
groups, we are taking it away
from these middle income

1011
00:46:10,150 --> 00:46:14,950
people and taxing their work
just as we subsidize the work

1012
00:46:14,950 --> 00:46:16,200
of the lowest income groups.

1013
00:46:16,200 --> 00:46:19,330

1014
00:46:19,330 --> 00:46:22,540
Now, so how do we think
about this?

1015
00:46:22,540 --> 00:46:24,186
Well, what we do in
this case is we go

1016
00:46:24,186 --> 00:46:26,180
to empirical evidence.

1017
00:46:26,180 --> 00:46:29,380
The EITC has grown enormously
over time.

1018
00:46:29,380 --> 00:46:31,240
And nicely, it's grown
differently

1019
00:46:31,240 --> 00:46:31,880
for different groups.

1020
00:46:31,880 --> 00:46:34,130
For example, it's gotten a lot
bigger for families with lots

1021
00:46:34,130 --> 00:46:37,080
of kids than for families
with no kids.

1022
00:46:37,080 --> 00:46:39,240
So what we can do is we can
actually study what's happened

1023
00:46:39,240 --> 00:46:41,010
to those kinds of families
over time as the

1024
00:46:41,010 --> 00:46:42,450
EITC has gone up.

1025
00:46:42,450 --> 00:46:45,260
What's happened to their
labor supply.

1026
00:46:45,260 --> 00:46:47,370
And what you see, it's
quite striking.

1027
00:46:47,370 --> 00:46:50,500
Which is there's been an
enormous increase in the

1028
00:46:50,500 --> 00:46:53,570
share, especially of single
mothers who have gone from not

1029
00:46:53,570 --> 00:46:56,520
working to working because
of the EITC.

1030
00:46:56,520 --> 00:46:59,160
But you don't see them working
less hard because of EITC.

1031
00:46:59,160 --> 00:47:01,450
That is, you see a lot of people
pulled-- if we go back

1032
00:47:01,450 --> 00:47:02,640
to our diagram.

1033
00:47:02,640 --> 00:47:05,650
See a lot of people pulled from
the zero earnings point

1034
00:47:05,650 --> 00:47:08,060
into the positive
earnings range.

1035
00:47:08,060 --> 00:47:10,220
But you don't see a lot of
people in the positive range

1036
00:47:10,220 --> 00:47:11,820
earning less.

1037
00:47:11,820 --> 00:47:14,020
So the good part of the EITC
has worked and the bad part

1038
00:47:14,020 --> 00:47:16,870
hasn't really cost
us anything.

1039
00:47:16,870 --> 00:47:17,650
Why is that?

1040
00:47:17,650 --> 00:47:19,950
Well, there could
be two reasons.

1041
00:47:19,950 --> 00:47:22,410
One could be because people are
a lot more responsive in

1042
00:47:22,410 --> 00:47:23,480
their decision to
work than their

1043
00:47:23,480 --> 00:47:24,480
decision how hard to work.

1044
00:47:24,480 --> 00:47:27,240
For example, you may not even
choose how hard you work.

1045
00:47:27,240 --> 00:47:30,610
Maybe you work 40 hours at
McDonald's or you don't work.

1046
00:47:30,610 --> 00:47:32,610
So the first answer is the
decision to work or not may be

1047
00:47:32,610 --> 00:47:36,520
the most elastic, more elastic
than how hard you work.

1048
00:47:36,520 --> 00:47:37,990
The second could be that people
just don't understand

1049
00:47:37,990 --> 00:47:40,470
this program and they know they
get a check, but they

1050
00:47:40,470 --> 00:47:41,910
don't know how to do
this kind of math.

1051
00:47:41,910 --> 00:47:43,370
So they say I now I get a
check if I go to work.

1052
00:47:43,370 --> 00:47:44,150
I'm going to work.

1053
00:47:44,150 --> 00:47:46,100
But they don't figure, by the
way, if I work one hour less,

1054
00:47:46,100 --> 00:47:50,290
maybe I'll lower my
tax bill by $21.

1055
00:47:50,290 --> 00:47:54,230
Whatever the reason, the
EITC has worked.

1056
00:47:54,230 --> 00:47:57,370
It has solved the problem
of the leaky bucket.

1057
00:47:57,370 --> 00:47:59,940
In fact, it's put money into
the bucket at the bottom.

1058
00:47:59,940 --> 00:48:03,100
In the sense that when the
government transfers you $1,

1059
00:48:03,100 --> 00:48:06,440
you actually earn more rather
than earning less.

1060
00:48:06,440 --> 00:48:08,960
So we're not only ending the
leak in the bucket at the

1061
00:48:08,960 --> 00:48:10,660
bottom of the income
distribution, we're actually

1062
00:48:10,660 --> 00:48:13,190
improving, offsetting some of
the 40% leak that comes from

1063
00:48:13,190 --> 00:48:18,150
the top by getting people to
work harder under this EITC.

1064
00:48:18,150 --> 00:48:20,460
We're transferring in a way
which actually improves

1065
00:48:20,460 --> 00:48:22,200
efficiency.

1066
00:48:22,200 --> 00:48:24,560
So basically, EITC we can think
of as sort of a patch of

1067
00:48:24,560 --> 00:48:26,460
the bucket.

1068
00:48:26,460 --> 00:48:27,470
It's a patch to the bucket.

1069
00:48:27,470 --> 00:48:30,440
You're actually helping address
leaks in the bucket by

1070
00:48:30,440 --> 00:48:31,120
doing this.

1071
00:48:31,120 --> 00:48:33,100
Now you might say
that's great.

1072
00:48:33,100 --> 00:48:36,590
That means that we have solved
our problems. We'll just get

1073
00:48:36,590 --> 00:48:38,940
money to the poor through the
EITC and there's no leak to

1074
00:48:38,940 --> 00:48:40,100
the bucket at the bottom.

1075
00:48:40,100 --> 00:48:42,610
But the problem is, once again
it's not that simple because

1076
00:48:42,610 --> 00:48:45,680
some people truly can't work.

1077
00:48:45,680 --> 00:48:46,890
Some people truly can't work.

1078
00:48:46,890 --> 00:48:47,840
So you need to have something
for those

1079
00:48:47,840 --> 00:48:49,520
that truly can't work.

1080
00:48:49,520 --> 00:48:52,390
So an ideal system would be one
where if you truly can't

1081
00:48:52,390 --> 00:48:53,760
work, we give you money.

1082
00:48:53,760 --> 00:48:56,330
If you can work, you
get the EITC.

1083
00:48:56,330 --> 00:48:58,640
Once again, the problem being
we have to decide who it is

1084
00:48:58,640 --> 00:49:01,540
that truly can't work
and who can work.

1085
00:49:01,540 --> 00:49:05,410
And so basically, how leaky the
bucket is at the bottom

1086
00:49:05,410 --> 00:49:08,630
will depend on how good a job
we can do at telling who the

1087
00:49:08,630 --> 00:49:11,100
people are who can work, who the
people are who can't work.

1088
00:49:11,100 --> 00:49:12,350